# TurboQuantex Integration & Vector Coding Rules

Whenever assisting the developer in this repository, you MUST follow these instructions automatically to interact with the codebase context.

---

## 1. Local Codebase Semantic Search (Mandatory)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **NEVER GUESS PATHS OR FUNCTION SIGNATURES.**
> Before answering questions about the workspace or writing code modifications, you must first execute the local semantic search tool to pull relevant code snippets.

### Search Command
Run the search CLI command using:
```bash
python .TurboQuantex/turbo_code.py search --index .TurboQuantex/codebase_index.tq --query "<search query matching requirements>" --top-k 3
```

### Context Integration
- Read the lines, files, and classes returned by the search command.
- Make sure to keep the code modifications aligned with the patterns found in the retrieved code blocks.

---

## 2. Incremental Index Updating

> [!TIP]
> **KEEP THE VECTOR INDEX SYNCED.**
> When you modify files in the codebase, you must update the TurboQuantex vector index to ensure the changes are reflected in future queries.

### Update Command
After any code changes are made, run:
```bash
python .TurboQuantex/turbo_code.py update --dir . --index .TurboQuantex/codebase_index.tq
```

---

## 3. Strict Offline Mode Compliance

- **No API Keys Needed**: All vector embeddings are processed 100% locally and offline via the SentenceTransformer (`all-MiniLM-L6-v2`) model or the local Flask daemon.
- **Do not introduce external API dependencies** unless the user explicitly requests it.
- **Daemon Acceleration**: If the local Flask daemon is running (port 5000), search queries and indexing operations will complete in milliseconds. Keep the Flask daemon running in the background for optimal performance.
